[1
Date: 9 Aug 2000 08:53:01 +0200
From: "Chris Griot" <christian.griot@ivi.admin.ch> and "M. Cosgriff"
<mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: BBC, 8 Aug 2000 and Electronic Telegraph, 9 Aug 2000 [edited

Swine fever hits 3 500 pigs
----------------------------
Farmers are mourning another blow to the swine industry after the discovery
of swine fever at a farm in Suffolk. About 3 500 pigs infected by the first
outbreak of classical swine fever (CSF) in Britain for 14 years are to be
slaughtered and destroyed. The Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Foods
(MAFF) said the infected animals were supplied by a breeding unit in
Norfolk which has also sent pigs to an Essex farm.
There were fears that the disease could spread rapidly throughout the
country. The MAFF, which refused to name the farm or give its precise
location, said it was establishing a large designated infected area in
Suffolk from which farmers would not be allowed to move pigs without a licence.
A spokesman said: "We want to establish if the disease originated on the
farm or was imported from elsewhere."
